category=Getting Started
description=<p>You want to know the height and width of a picture stored in a file, without visibly displaying it to the user. For example, you might want to display information about the pictures in a folder as part of a content management system.</p>
discussion=<p>This custom function is called with a statement such as the following:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">get</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> imageFileDimensions(&quot;/Disk/Folder/Picture File&quot;)</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> item 2 of imageFileDimensions(myFile) into theHeight</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">set</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> the naturalDimensions of </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">me</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> to imageFileDimensions(it)</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The &quot;imageFileDimensions&quot; function gets the size--height and width--of a picture file in any of the formats that Revolution can import. It does this by importing the file as an image object and checking the new image's height and width properties.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>When the file is imported, the new image appears on the screen. Since it's only going to be there long enough to get the height and width, we don't want the user to see the annoying flash of the image appearing and disappearing, so the first thing this handler does is to use the <font face="Courier" size="11">lock screen</font> command to prevent changes from appearing in the window.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>With the screen safely locked, the handler uses the <font face="Courier" size="11">import</font> command to import the file into the stack, where it becomes a new image. The <font face="Courier" size="11">width</font> and <font face="Courier" size="11">height</font> of this image are <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>automatically</i></font> set to the picture's natural width and height, so we can check these properties to get the <font face="Courier" size="11">width</font> and <font face="Courier" size="11">height</font> of the original picture file. Once the handler has gotten the properties, we no longer need the imported image, so we delete it. This removes the image object we created with the import command, leaving the original picture file where it was.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Finally, the handler returns the width and height, separated by a comma (the , operator). The calling handler can use both, or (if it only needs one of the height or width) can check item 1 or item 2 of the return value.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>What if the calling handler passed a file path that isn't in one of the formats Revolution can import--for example, what if the theFilePath is a text file? If we try to import such a file, the import command will cause an <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>execution error</i></font>, and we don't want to make users deal with the Error window. (It looks sloppy.) We could check the extension of the file and reject files that don't have the proper extension, but a file might be mislabeled with the wrong extension.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Whenever an error occurs in a script, it sends an <font face="Courier" size="11">errorDialog</font> message is sent to the object whose script caused the error, and the <font face="Courier" size="11">errorDialog</font> handler is executed. The <font face="Courier" size="11">errorDialog</font> handler in this example displays an error message to the user.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Note:</b></font> in this example, we initially set <font face="Courier" size="11">the lockErrorDialogs</font> to true to prevent the Revolution debugger intercepting the error if <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Script Debug Mode</i></font> is on.</p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Getting the dimensions of a picture file
solution=<p><font color="#0000FF">function</font> imageFileDimensions theFilePath</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">lock</font> screen <font color="#68228B">-- so user doesn't see the following shenanigans</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">lock</font> error dialogs <font color="#68228B">-- prevent error window if import fails and debug mode is on</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">import</font> paint from file theFilePath <font color="#68228B">-- creates a new image</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">unlock</font> error dialogs</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">put</font> the <font color="#FF0000">width</font> of last image into myWidth</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">put</font> the <font color="#FF0000">height</font> of last image into myHeight</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">delete</font> last image <font color="#68228B">-- get rid of image we created</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">unlock</font> screen</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">return</font> myWidth,myHeight</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> imageFileDimensions</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font color="#980517">on</font> errorDialog theDetails-- executed <font color="#980517">if</font> the <font color="#0000FF">import</font> causes a <font color="#FF0000">script</font> error</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">answer</font> theDetails</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">beep</font></p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">answer</font> &quot;There was a problem accessing the file data.&quot;\\</p>\n<p>      &amp; <font color="#0000FF">return</font> &amp; <font color="#0000FF">return</font> &amp; \\</p>\n<p>      &quot;Picture files must be in one of the following formats:&quot; &amp; \\</p>\n<p><font color="#0000FF">      return</font> &amp; &quot;PNG, JPEG, GIF, PICT, BMP, XWD/XBM/XPM, or PBM/PGM/PPM.&quot;</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> errorDialog</p>
title=Getting the dimensions of a picture file